snippet.title: What is Machining?
snippet.description:
America needs more machinists!   

We are fortunate enough to sit on a local advisory panel for the Mid-East Career & Technology Centers Precision Machining Program.  It's a great program for High School Juniors and Seniors to prepare them for careering in machining.  

In an effort to raise awareness for both machining in general as well as the Mid-East program, we made this short film!

If you're a High School student in the central Ohio area, consider checking out Mid-East's program in Zanesville!

snippet.title: How to Anodize Aluminum - My approach on DIY small scale anodizing by DeeWorks
snippet.description:
*** The titanium disc that you see in this video are available to purchase at https://www.anodizingsupplycanada.com/ as well as several other aluminum anodizing supply ***

This is a video to show how I made my home based anodizing line and to show the convenience of using it. I am not here to advertise my service as I only anodize my own product, but i'd be happy if I motivate a few to get started on their own!

I've been wanting to make one of these video for awhile. As you can see english is not my first language so I make a lot of mistake here and there. If you hear anything wrong or have question about something I have not explained, please feel free to let me know! I will try to answer each and every question and comments I will have on my video. There is a lot of video out there on youtube showing how to do a first try using car battery charger and how to set up your acid concentration. I left aside that aspect of anodizing and decided to make this video to show how I made a permanent anodizing line in my garage in a 8' x 15' room. 

Doing anodizing for about 5 years now, I've started with tank smaller than these and slowly acquired knowledge and time saving trick. My success rate is well over 98% of perfectly anodized parts, and the 2% scrap were all mostly due to poor cleaning. It still surprise me every time I finish a batch!

In the video we see the Titanium Rack that I also sell and been using for the last 4 years now, they have speeded up my process by alot and helped me to make my own anodizing much more worth it. With the combination of the titanium racking, the temperature controller on each chemical/color & the gutted air conditioning unit for acid bath cooling, it takes about 45 minutes of my time for a full batch. Most of the time it just all run by itself.

If you like what you see, please subscribe to my channel for more DIY stuff, machining and car video!

Thanks for watching!

snippet.title: How To CNC Cut Metal For Under $400
snippet.description:
The dream is to be able to CNC cut metal parts in your garage for the least money possible. Well, I think I've got a solution for y'all: The 1310 CNC. snippet.title: Introduction to Electrical Discharge Machining | Learn to Burn
snippet.description:
Welcome to the first episode of the Everything EDM - Learn to Burn series. Zero Tolerance LLC zeroes in on electrical discharge machining (EDM), starting from the basic concepts.

There are many different names for this subtractive manufacturing process: spark machining, spark eroding, die sinking... the list goes on and electrical discharge machining is considered a "non traditional" or "non conventional" machining process. This video, Introduction to Electrical Discharge Machining, will show you how, what, and why. 

00:15 Introduction to Zero Tolerance and how they use electrical discharge machining to create their plastic injection molds. 
2:14 Beginning the electrical discharge machining process of an intricate mold.
3:37 Using the electrode holder and how it works.
8:43 Continuing the electrical discharge machining process of an intricate mold.
11:24 Quick lesson about how the electrode and voltage create the spark and cut the metal. 
13:31 No broken cutters with hardened steel and EDM.
14:01 Thank you and closing

Stay tuned for next month's episode that will talk all about wire EDM and fast hole EDM.

snippet.title: Cutting aluminum parts with 3018 Pro CNC, making an E3D V6 hotend mount for the Sapphire Plus CoreXY
snippet.description:
In this video, we will make some aluminum parts with this super cheap CNC 3018 Pro for the Sapphire Plus CoreXY printer. If you’ve watched my previous videos, this printer has a few minor issues, but considering that it costs less than $400 and has a very sturdy frame, it actually has a lot of potential. It’s able to print at 150mm/s with pretty good quality. But, when I try to print at over 200mm/s, the hotend couldn’t melt the filament fast enough. So, I decided to upgrade the hotend to a E3D V6 Volcano which should do a much better job than the stock one.

Since the X carriage has a bit of a unique design that doesn’t fit any other hotends, I have to redesign it. If I just 3D print one, I’m worried that the high temperature of the heater block will melt the plastic. Even if I use filament with higher temperature resistance like ASA, which softens only when the temperature grows above 100 degree celsius, it may still not be the best solution, since when you print at higher speed, you may need to print at an even higher temperature to melt the plastic fast enough to keep up with the speed. So, a better option would be to use some aluminum bars to make the parts.

This is the cheapest CNC in the world, the 3018 Pro. It only cost around $150. It was designed to do some light engraving on soft materials like MDF or acrylic, so obviously, it’s not capable of cutting metal. The price of the 3018 CNC ranges from $150 to $350. They are basically the same, with the same frame, same hardware. Some of the more expensive ones may have added limit switches, the emergency stop button and some other cosmetic upgrades.

So, I just bought the cheapest one and upgraded the spindle from the stock 80-watt one to a 500-watt one, which cost $70. I also added 3 limit switches on each axis to home the machine, which cost $3. I got a probe sensor, which was DIY by connecting 2 wires to the mainboard, which cost $1 or less, and finally, emergency stop buttons, one for the spindle and one for the machine, which cost $8. All other parts are stock parts. 

After all upgrades, the total price of this machine is $230. I also made an enclosure, as this machine is quite noisy when it cuts things. I used less than 4 meters of 2020 aluminum extrusions, which cost around $35, 2 pieces of laminated MDF from Home Depot, which cost $12, and one piece of a one-eighth-inch acrylic sheet and some magnetic tape, which cost $30.  So, the total cost of the machine with the enclosure costs less than $300. It actually doesn’t look too bad, but the most important part is, can it really cut aluminum? Let’s find out.


Please also watch my 500w spindle upgrade video:
https://youtu.be/xD2_JvOSx7s

snippet.title: The cheapest $149 CNC 3018, cut and mill aluminum is now possible with 500 W spindle upgrade
snippet.description:
In my previous videos, I used this CNC 3018 Pro to make some aluminum 3D printer parts. As many of you are interested in how I upgraded this $149 CNC to cut aluminum, I am going to make a series of videos to show you everything including the hardware upgrade, firmware configuration, using Fusion 360 CAD for 3D modeling and using Fusion 360 CAM to generate G-code for the CNC.

In this video, we will start with the most important part, upgrading the 500W spindle. You will see the detail process, what hardware and 3D printed models you need for this upgrade. I will also show some aluminum cutting footage so you can expect what you can get after the 500W spindle is installed.

snippet.title: Making An Inverted Dovetail Cutter | Chamfer Cutter On the Mill
snippet.description:
G'day everyone,

Today I'll be showing you the process I undertook to make my simple cutter to make the gib strips for the mini lathe. Having just bought my new mill, tooling was quite limited, so I decided to make a 60 degree chamfer cutter using some TCMT inserts that I already use for the lathe. Since this tool would not be used for many parts, I thought it be best to make it in house from some mild steel, than buy an off the shelf part. It is not a perfect tool, but I learned a lot through out the process.

Cheers

#machining #DIY

snippet.title: Making A Steel Quick Change Tool Post And Tool Holders For The Mini Lathe
snippet.description:
G'day everyone,

The time has come to replace my old quick change tool post that I made on this channel at the beginning of the year. It has served me well for a long time, and it has never let me down. However it is made from aluminum, and now that I turn steel more often than I used to, I have decided to upgrade to a steel tool post. Now that I have my new vertical milling machine I will now be able to make it, plus 7 tool holders, in the workshop using about $20 worth of mild steel.
